pr_review_comment_body:
So what I was thinking when I suggested this was something a little different:

```python
def operation_test_method(op):
    def test_method(self):
        pass   # basically "validate_request_call"
    return test_method

def resource_test_class(resource):
    attrs = {}
    for op_id, op in resource.operations.items():
        attrs["test_{}".format(op_id)] = operation_test_method(op)
    return type("{}Test".format(resource.name), (SwaggerResourceTest,), attrs)

BucketsTest = resource_test_class(resources['Buckets'])   # or whatever the syntax is
CollectionsTest = resource_test_class(resources['Collections'])    # etc.
```

This approach means you don't have to explicitly handle metaclasses, which could be easier to read. Another approach might be to use a class decorator:

```python
def operation_test_method(op):
    def method(self):
        pass  # again, basically validate_request_call

def resource_test_case(resource):
    def decorator(cls):
        for op_id, op in resource.operations.items():
            setattr(cls, "test_{}".format(op_id), operation_test_method(op))
        return cls

    return decorator

@resource_test_case(resources['Buckets'])
class BucketsTest(SwaggerTest):
    pass
```

But having reread this a bunch of times, I think the hardest part to read was just the diff. Reading the new file, it isn't that confusing, except for a couple of quirks in how I think you are interfacing with Bravado.

Unless I'm missing something, the `load` and `cast` of this type_caster template and the first one (for `std::chrono::duration`) is almost entirely duplicated code: `load` and `cast` across the two types only seem to differ meaningfully on one line (since one is a time point containing a duration, the other is a duration directly).  It would be very nice to put these into a pair of templated helper function to avoid this duplication.  Perhaps something like the following (untested, and you can probably improve upon it):

```C++
template <typename Duration, typename Period> Duration duration_loader(Duration &value, handle src) {
    // ...
}
template <typename Duration> duration_caster(const Duration &src) {
    // ...
}

    // In the std::chrono::duration type caster:
    bool load(handle src, bool) { return duration_loader<type, type::period>(value, src); }
    static handle cast(const std::chrono::duration<Rep, Period> &src, return_value_policy /* policy */, handle /* parent */) {
        return duration_caster(src);
    }

    // and in the generic clock type caster:
    bool load(handle src, bool) {
        Duration dur;
        if !(duration_loader<type, type::period>(dur, src)) return false;
        value = time_point<Clock, Duration>(dur);
        return true;
    }
    static handle cast(const std::chrono::time_point<Clock, Duration> &src, return_value_policy /* policy */, handle /* parent */) {
        return duration_caster(src.time_since_epoch());
    }
```

Minor: might as well name it `static_strings` or the like? (unlike all other fields of `internals`, this one you would never actually read, it's just there for storage with static lifetime and doesn't really have to do much with types)

Also, in case we ever need it again?

```cpp
const char* detail::strdup(const std::string& what) {
    auto& internals = get_internals();
    internals.static_strings.emplace_front(what);
    return internals.static_strings.front().c_str();
}

@chrisforrette 
I think these get_queryset methods are problematic, because Django might use them automatically.

I am not sure, but this might get changed to be a private/local function?

Otherwise: can this be made to call `super` / parent classes (easily)?
Maybe similar to QueryManagerMixin from https://github.com/carljm/django-model-utils/blob/master/model_utils/managers.py#L198, where it also extends `__init__`.

With Django 1.7 the default is:

    def get_queryset(self):
        return self._queryset_class(self.model, using=self._db, hints=self._hints)

I had problems because this `get_queryset` method overwrote the queryset from `objects = BaseManager.from_queryset(BaseQuerySet)()` being used.

I am now using `objects = MyManager.from_queryset(MyQuerySet)()`, where `MyQuerySet` inherits from ActivatorQuerySet.
